text.0:
A claim that Kenya's deputy president is heading to the US to "congratulate president-elect Donald Trump" is :cross_mark: FALSE.

The office of deputy president denied the claim and said William Ruto had not travelled: https://t.co/fzR5JhX1Ye
text.1:
A Facebook post claiming to show a fighter jet that was shot down by anti-aircraft missiles outside Mekelle, the capital of Tigray Regional State, is :cross_mark: FALSE.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: Some of the images in the post have been online from as far back as 2013: https://t.co/QYdKZJbg7V
text.2:
:police_car_light: HOAX: A Google form with instructions on how to apply for loans offered by ‘Waraka LoansKE’ is fake.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: Waraka LoansKE is not a registered lender, and the mobile money number given on their form is registered to a different organisation: https://t.co/HoOnwahyTe
text.3:
:police_car_light: HOAX: A Facebook post claiming that @SafaricomPLC is gifting its subscribers KSh 7,000 is fake.

:warning_selector: The telecommunications company has officially distanced itself from the giveaway: https://t.co/HFvK8VlUtZ
text.4:
An image shared on Facebook claiming to show people holding a banner with the words “Satan loves Kamala” is ALTERED.

:magnifying_glass_tilted_right: The image combines a photo featuring US vice president-elect Kamala Harris with a photo in which the text has been manipulated: https://t.co/UH3ER2qu6Y
text.5:
A Facebook post claiming that First Lady Margaret Kenyatta is giving Kenyans KSh 20,000 in celebration of her son’s birthday is :cross_mark: FALSE.

:warning_selector: The page making this claim impersonates the First Lady: https://t.co/D2XBpZUibm
